snippet.title: Is Biking in Paris Safe? Plus a lot of cheese desserts at the end
snippet.description:
Is it safe to ride bikes in Paris? We think biking is safe in Paris - you can rent bikes and get 5€ off your rental with http://bikeabouttours.com - Or just take one of their awesome tours. Follow our route here https://ridewithgps.com/trips/32587522 and as always, you can help me make better videos at http://patreon.com/jayswanson and then find me on the internet in all of the usual spots:

Grab my guide to Paris here: http://bit.ly/ParisVloggersGuide

Cheese event by Oh My Milk - this one was #ohmysweetcheese http://www.ohmysweetcheese.com/

More swag here:
http://bit.ly/ShirtOfTheMonth (shirts and hat)
http://bit.ly/JaysGearList (my gear and books)
https://gum.co/camerafour (Disposable Camera Four digital scans)

Follow me here:
http://twitter.com/jayonaboat
http://instagram.com/jayswanson

Music by: Tank Top Boyz

My name is Jay Swanson - I'm an American writer living in Paris on an artist visa and hoping to make the city of light my home base - at least for the foreseeable future. I write science-fiction and fantasy, vlog daily, and love pizza a little too much.

Links below to Amazon are affiliate links - meaning if you click through them and buy something, I'll get some pennies. Thanks! (The FTC wants me to tell you that up front)

FAQ:
How long have you lived in France? On and off for over two years.

What do you miss most about ho- NACHOS

You're always talking about living on some ship. WHAT SHIP? - I made a "Draw My Life" video that explains a lot here: https://youtu.be/-MrvL37jTKM

Where are you from originally? - Pullman, Washington - a small university/agricultural town near Idaho (and yes, the potatoes are amazing).

What do you film with? - I've made a lot of changes recently, but I try to keep my gear list up to date if you want to see what I use and buy some for yourself: http://bit.ly/JaysGearList

What do you edit with? - Adobe Premiere - it's pretty much all I've ever used since high school.

Aren't you ever freaked out by leaving your camera behind to film yourself? - Yep. But not too badly - I tend to be careful when I do.

Why are you living in #Paris? - Because I've always wanted to; I feel at home here: https://youtu.be/4Vivf6MqMxQ

Do you speak French? Oui. https://youtu.be/va1QjaHgij8

You talk a lot about the books you're working on, what are they about? - They're sci-fi (and fantasy) and I've got a decent pitch for you here: https://youtu.be/W2bKt4_Tp4E

Do you make money off YouTube? - Ha, no. I wish. It took me over 500 videos to make my first total $100 off adsense. I think it will slowly change, but VERY slowly.

I really enjoy your videos, how can I support you? - The easiest and best way to support me is through Patreon, where you can pitch in as little as $1/mo to help me make better videos: http://patreon.com/jayswanson

I don't trust this Patreon thing - can I just paypal you? - Here's my ko-fi if that's your thing (and coffee is your game): https://ko-fi.com/jayswanson

But I want to send you something tangible! - I do have a wishlist on Amazon, though it's a bit complicated with the international shipping situation. This is the US one: http://amzn.to/2ykS9Ux

And here's the French wishlist: http://bit.ly/JaysFrenchWishList

Thanks for watching!

comments.textDisplay:
There is one reason why riding WITHOUT a helmet for proficient cyclists is preferable, streets with motorists. When cycling most motorists leave around 60cm (2ft) when confronted with a bicycle. That is enough for the cyclists to not feel crowded. However, when motorists see cyclists WITH a helmet that distance drops to 45cm (1.5ft). That holds true for ALL 'cycle cities', including the cities like Amsterdam, Berlin, Copenhagen, Munich and the like. Various scientific research has been done and it seems to be 'hard' evidence.

However, those who are not proficient should wear one AND USE LESS CROWED venues to practice. For instance, where cities like Amsterdam, Copenhagen or Utrecht, are a joy to bike through for the proficient cyclists, please, if you are not, stick to the parks and less travelled streets.

And, yes, I couldn't leave it alone 😉

replies.textDisplay:
+Martin Shaves & Reviews
April 8th sunset 20:31 twilight 21:04
Next day sunset is 1.5 minutes later as is twilight. Each day you have 3.5 minutes more of daylight.

Basically you need to arrive 5 minutes before sunset for that photo and your spot scooped out before that. Then you have around an hour and half to make the most of blue hour. Cheers. 🙂

comments.textDisplay: Those cheese dishes made me drool. I love french cheese, but in the US (at least where I live) it is hard to find, expensive, and doesn't taste as good. I'm not sure why the taste is different, but I have 2 hypotheses. First, a lot of cheese I've had in France is not pasteurized but unpasteurized cheese cannot be imported in the US and pasteurization seems to destroy flavor. Second, Americans are used to very, very mild cheeses, so that's the kind of cheese that gets sent to the US. For example, I bought a camembert from Normandy at Trader Joe's. It tasted nothing like the camembert I ate in Normandy. Anybody else have an explanation?

replies.textDisplay:
+Yvonne Rahmes In the US and in a some European cities, there are docked bikes like this (https://www.nydailynews.com/resizer/CV2bCRfiK0eW3zpmlxmcoc6kzdw=/800x0/arc-anglerfish-arc2-prod-tronc.s3.amazonaws.com/public/CI7GXW26SC32RIM5EJTATGGQUA.jpg) and you download an app and can rent them for a set time. Then when you're finished, you find a docking station and put it back.

Barcelona has one, but it is restricted to residents, for example. I believe London has a dock system as well.

Dockless is like the Lime (green) scooters. Lime started with dockless bicycles and electric bicycles, though those are becoming less common and scooters seem to be their preferred tech.

comments.textDisplay:
I biked around Paris a few days ago on the Velib system. I can say the 8e, 9e, and 2e have crazy amount of traffic, and pretty suicidal. I stopped just for 1 min against a curb, and a city bus honked and brushed passed me within inches. Fk that. Elsewhere biking is a little bit easier, but you still have to be on alert. One thing about Paris, you can bike in the opposite direction of a 1 way street on a narrow 3 foot wide sharrows and you have to be really alert when you pass a car as the streets are narrow. As a pedestrian, you really have to worry most about people on motorscooters, most of them simply ignore traffic rules, and the crosswalk.

As a member of nyc's only bike coop, I did visit 3 bike coops here in Paris and was happy to see/learn about the bicycling culture here despite the infrastructure difficulties. I didn't have time to try your game.
